A very beautiful church discovered by chance during our walk near the Luxembourg Gardens. Very calm and pleasant, you can gather there and appreciate the architecture without problem.

Although disfigured and stripped of all its decoration in the destructive enthusiasm of the post-Second Vatican Council, with the support of Andr√© Malraux, the St Jacques du Hautpas church remains a heritage site of interest, a stop on the Parisian route to St Jacques de Compostela. A few remains bear witness to its former splendor. The old high altar is visible in the northern part, in the chapel dedicated to the faithful who died between 1914 and 1918. The chapel of the virgin is very pleasant.

Roman Catholic parish church in Paris. The cathedral is located at the corner of Saint-Jacques and Rue de l'Appe in the fifth arrondissement of Paris. The time of construction of the Saint-Jacques-du-Haute-Pa church dates back to the first half of the 17th century.  Until 1630, it belonged to the 12th century.  Order of St.  John of the earth was a small chapel.  In 1572, Benedictine monks from Saint-Magloire Abbey also settled next to it. In 1675 architect D. Gittard developed a new project for the reconstruction of this temple.  The main works were completed after 10 years, and in May 1685 the church was re-consecrated.  In 1697, next to the temple according to the project of L. Bruant, the chapel of the Holy Mother of God was built.

Very beautiful church which houses some treasures  This church, which in the Middle Ages welcomed pilgrims on their way to Compostela, today contains several works representing the figure of Saint James.  A medieval stone statue where we see Saint James wearing a wide-brimmed pilgrim's hat garnished with shells presenting the book of the new law and, for around thirty years, thanks to a private donation, a stocking wooden relief showing Saint James adoring the Virgin who appears to him  These two works are located after the sacristy and are difficult to see without disturbing the assembly if an office is in progress. You should therefore take the trouble to look at the timetables before coming.  Likewise, it is important to specify that this church closes at lunchtime

This church, a historic building, has a long and controversial history. In 1180 the Brothers of Altospacio, Italy, settled (that's where the name Du Haut Pas comes from). There were only fields and low houses. In 1459 Pope Pius II dissolved the order, but some decided to stay. In 1572 Catherine de' Medici installed some expelled Benedictines. A church is built, but it quickly becomes too small. In 1630, work on the current church began, which continued for a long time. Inside are the tombs of the astronomer Jean-Dominique Cassini (1625 - 1712) and the mathematician Philippe de La Hire (1640 - 1718).

Devolved by Catherine de Medici to the Benedictines of the former Abbey of Saint Magloire then assigned to the Oratorians in 1620, the Church became a parish under the name of Saint Jacques the Minor in 1630 and rebuilt on the order of Gaston d'Orl√©ans, brother of Louis XIII who lived in the neighboring Medici Palace. The work was completed in 1685, led by various architects such as Daniel Gittard, Lib√©ral Bruant..... The new parish will maintain close links with the neighboring and recently installed Port-Royal Abbey of Faubourg Saint Jacques. The name "Haut Pas" comes from the occupation in the 12th century of the ancient church by Hospitaller Brothers from the village of Altopascio near Lucca in Italy.
A large, clear, tall church, built in the classical style. Some paintings in the Saint-Sulpician style, the relics of Magloire and a beautiful statue of a pilgrim of Saint-Jacques.

Church built on the Via di San Giacomo which connects Paris to Compostela by the brotherhood of San Giacomo of Altopascio (Lucca) - a location on the Via Francigena known for its famous welcome of pilgrims. Altopascio in French became Haute Pau. Saint Ignatius of Loyola was hosted in the adjacent pilgrims' hostel

Built on 12th century land belonging to the Hospitaller Brothers of Altopascio (Italy), the ‚Äúdu-Haut-Pas‚Äù church, whose construction was built in the 16th century, took the name of this village. The Saint-Jacques-du-Haut-Pas church is one of the rare Parisian churches whose choir faces west. The tombs of Philippe de la Hire, mathematician, and Giovanni Domenico Cassini (astronomer and first director of the Paris observatory) are buried there.

Beautiful church full of history and in particular that of Father Cochin who founded the hospital of the same name. Located on one of the oldest thoroughfares in Paris, former Gallic track and Gallo-Roman road to Orl√©ans. Beautiful light inside conducive to meditation. 2 organs. Take your time

Beautiful church, large and bright, not very far on foot from the Luxembourg Gardens and whose priest gave (still gives??) the blessing to pilgrims leaving for Santiago de Compostela...since it is on this path! The Saint-Jacques-du-Haut-Pas church is one of the rare Parisian churches whose choir faces west, following the reversal of the plan decided during the reconstruction of the building in the 17th century. Two very beautiful organs are inside, one of which is at eye level.... √âdouard Branly was a parishioner of this church!

This is the first time I have entered this place of PRAYER. What did me good was the time of contemplation before the Blessed SACRAMENT. Then attend Mass at 6:30 p.m.  Mass celebrated by the Student Priest on the feast of the two martyrs St Cornelius and St Cyprian.  He preached to us a very good homily about the pagan centurion who had great faith to ask Jesus to heal his slave who was dying.  He had total trust in Christ without being Jewish.  My Lord, I am not worthy for you to enter my house, but say one word and my slave will be healed.  The proof is that at this word of faith from the centurion his slave regained his strength and was healed and returned to work.  Sincerely Rose Marie LOEMBE.
